      dek: `This is the unglamorous chapter that keeps your shoot from getting shut down. Free locations, a permit when you need one, and short-term insurance are the three pieces of paperwork that separate "we filmed a movie" from "we got kicked out of a coffee shop."`,
      seoTitle: "Short Film Locations, Permits & Insurance | Filmmaker Genius",
      seoDesc: "Locations, permits, and insurance for a short film — how to find and lock free locations, when you need a film permit, and the short-term insurance that keeps your shoot alive. Chapter 7 of Producing the Short Film.",
      body: `
    <p>Nobody dreams of the paperwork. But the fastest way to lose a shoot day isn't a broken camera — it's a location owner who never really said yes, a police officer who asks for a permit you don't have, or a rental house that won't release gear because you have no insurance. This chapter is your defense against all three. Get these right in prep and they're invisible; skip them and any one can end your day.</p>

    <h2>Locking locations for free</h2>

    <p>On a short, your location strategy is simple: <em>write to places you can already get.</em> The apartment you live in, the bar owned by a friend, the office you can borrow on a Sunday. Great short-film location scouting isn't about finding the perfect space — it's about finding the good-enough space you can actually secure at zero cost. And "secure" is the key word: a verbal "sure, film here" is not a location. Get it in writing.</p>

    <ul class="spec-list">
      <li><b>Get a signed location release.</b> A one-page agreement that says you can film there and use the footage in your film — signed by whoever actually controls the space, not the barista who happens to be working. This is what lets you distribute the film later.</li>
      <li><b>Scout with a phone.</b> Photograph every angle, note the power outlets, the natural light at your shoot time, the noise (a location under a flight path is a sound nightmare). What looks great to your eye can be unusable to your mic.</li>
      <li><b>Confirm access, not just permission.</b> When can you load in? Where do people park? Is there a bathroom, a place to feed the crew, a spot for the actors to change? A location without logistics is a trap.</li>
      <li><b>Have a backup.</b> Locations fall through — the owner gets cold feet, the space floods. A produced short always has a plan B for its key location.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Permits and insurance, demystified</h2>

    <p>Two things scare first-timers and shouldn't. First, <strong>permits.</strong> Whether you need a film permit depends mostly on where you shoot and your footprint. On <em>private property</em> you have permission for, you generally don't need a city permit — you need the owner's release. On <em>public property</em> — a street, a park, a sidewalk — you often do, especially with visible gear, a crew, or anything that disrupts the space. When in doubt, the local film office is a free phone call, and they'd rather help you do it right than catch you doing it wrong.</p>

    <p>Second, <strong>insurance.</strong> Short-term production insurance sounds like a big-movie thing, but it's cheap, sold by the day or project, and it's often the gate to everything else: most permits require proof of it, most rental houses won't hand over a camera without it, and many locations want to see a certificate before they let you in. A basic general-liability policy also protects <em>you</em> if someone trips over a cable. Budget it as a real line (you did, back in Chapter 2) and buy it early — leaving it to the last week can block your whole shoot.</p>

    <div class="pullquote">A verbal yes is not a location, a shrug is not a permit, and hoping nothing goes wrong is not insurance. The paperwork is boring right up until the afternoon it saves your shoot.</div>

    <div class="callout">
      <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
      <p>Get the location release signed at the scout, not on shoot day. Goodwill is highest before you've descended on someone's space with eight people and a light stand, and lowest the moment something goes slightly wrong. Bring the one-page form to the walkthrough, explain it plainly — "this just says we can film here and use it; we'll leave it exactly as we found it" — and get the signature while everyone's still excited.</p>
    </div>
  `,
